Introduction¶

For decades there has been a heated debate on whether aliens exist or not. The biggest evidence for aliens existing is the large amount of UFO sightings throughout the years. The purpose of this tutorial is to show how to collect and analyze UFO sighting data in order to see if there is a expaination for UFO sightings like people's belief in the extraterrestrial intensified by movies released at the time.

Data Collection¶

In this tutorial, we will be using 2 datasets collected from Kaggle

 UFO sightings dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/NUFORC/ufo-sightings
 TMDB 5000 Movie dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/tmdb/tmdb-movie-metadata

The UFO sightings dataset is collected by the National UFO Reporting Center (NUFORC) which specilizes in recording UFO sightings from all over the world.

The TMDB 5000 Movie dataset is collected from The Movie Database (TMDb) which, since 2008, has had public users add and edit missing/incorrect data.

All you have to do is downloading both datasets from kaggle into the same folder as this notebook.

Movie data¶

The code below collects the movie data and only keeps the movies that have Science Fiction or Fantasy tags since those movies are the most likely to have aliens and might intensify the viewers' beliefs in the extraterrestrial.

In [7]:
# to figure out if the movie has a Science Fiction or Fantasy tag
def search(gen):
    for g in gen:
        if g['name'] == 'Science Fiction':
            return 'Science Fiction'
        if g['name'] == 'Fantasy':
            return 'Fantasy'
    return np.nan

Looking at the UFO data¶

In this analysis part, we will look at different features of the UFO Sightings data and see if the features show any patterns.

Most of the sightings tend to happen in developed countries around the world. There are very few markers in third world countries. It could be that the people in those countries don't know about the National UFO Reporting Center (NUFORC) or have no way to get in contact with the center. Also, this could be because of movies not being released in third-world counties.

How long did the UFO stay?¶

Duration¶

By ploting the durations of the UFO sightings over time, we can see that before the 1940's the durations of the sightings were very small, not even an hour (3600 seconds). However, as time went on, the durations started getting longer. This could be do to the fact that there is not a lot of data from before 1940's. I did cap the duration to 50 hours, because more than 2 days seemed unprobable for a UFO sighting.

What did the UFOs look like?¶

There are two descriptions of the UFOs in the dataset. One is shape, where is reporter is told to describe the shape of the UFO as best they can. The other is comments, where is a more general description of the UFO.

Shape¶

The following code combines similar reported shapes into one catagory so that the frequency of each shape is accurate.

In [14]:
df['shape'] = df['shape'].replace(np.nan, 'unknown')
df['shape'] = df['shape'].replace('other', 'unknown')
df['shape'] = df['shape'].replace('changed', 'changing')
df['shape'] = df['shape'].replace('round', 'circle')
df['shape'].unique()

Comments¶

WordCloud¶

With the comments data, we can create a word cloud. In a word cloud, the more frequently a word was used in the comments, the larger the word shows up in the cloud. This is a easy visual way to see which were the most common words used in really large strings like in the comments.

In [17]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud
import re

x = df["comments"].replace(re.compile('\&\#\d\d'), '')
text = x.dropna().str.cat(sep='')
text = text.replace('NUFORC Note', '')
text = text.replace('&quot;', '')
wordcloud = WordCloud().generate(text)
In [18]:
wordcloud = WordCloud(max_font_size=40).generate(text)
plt.figure()
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

Looking at the word cloud, the largest words are pretty much the same as the shapes, bright lights moving around in the sky.

When Did the Sightings Happen?¶

By ploting the frequency of sightings per year, we can see that, in recent years, there has been a sharp increase in the number of UFO sightings, upto almost 8000 in a year!

In [19]:
from collections import Counter
df['year'] = df['date'].apply(lambda x: x.year)

x = Counter(df['year'])
labels, values = zip(*x.items())

occur = pd.DataFrame(data = list(labels), columns=['year'])
occur['freq'] = list(values)

occur = occur.sort_values(by='year').dropna()

plt.figure(1, figsize=(20,5))
plt.plot(occur['year'], occur['freq'])
m, b = np.polyfit(occur['year'], occur['freq'], 1)
plt.ylim((0,8000))
plt.plot(occur['year'], m*occur['year'] + b, '-')
plt.title('The Frequency of UFO Sightings Through Time')
plt.ylabel('Frequency of a UFO Sightings')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.show()
print(m)

sight_freq = occur

42.7958743443

The number of sightings started to increase in the 1960s and then sharply increased in the 1990s. The slope of the line of best fit is about 45. Therefore, starting from the 1960, on rough average, the number of UFO sightings was increasing by about 45 sightings per year. The dip in the last year is likely because the recent data has not been processed or even reported.

In [20]:
df['time to report'] = df['date posted'] - df['datetime']
print (df['time to report'].max())
print (df['time to report'].median())

35106 days 00:00:00
26 days 01:00:00

For many of these sightings, it can take a long time, even years before the sighting is reported. For this data, the maximum time that it took someone to report a UFO slighting was 35106 days or 96 years! The median reporting time was about 26 days. I did not use the mean, because it was heavily skewed by extreme numbers like the 96 years mentioned before. However, 26 days is still a large number and the large delay in reporting can cast doubt on the accuracy in the reports and the validity of the sighting.

Machine Learning and Hypothesis Testing¶

Could it be the movies?¶

After looking at all the exploratory data, I feel that there could be a correlation between when science fiction and fantasy movies are released and the number of UFO sightings.

The following code is analysing science fiction and fantasy movie releasings. It is possible that with the increase in these movies, people would be more likely to think they have seen a UFO. My null hypothesis is that there is little to no correlation between the number of UFO sightings and the number of science fiction and fantasy movies released. In order to reject the null hypothesis, the p-value of the regression should be less than .05 as that would suggest a strong relationship.

In [22]:
df_combined = pd.merge(occur, sight_freq, on=['year'], how='inner')
plt.scatter(df_combined['movies'], df_combined['freq'])
m, b = np.polyfit(df_combined['movies'], df_combined['freq'], 1)
plt.ylim((0,8000))
plt.plot(df_combined['movies'], m*df_combined['movies'] + b, '-')
plt.title('The Number of UFO Sightings vs the Number of Syfy and Fantasy Movies released each year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Syfy and Fantasy Movies')
plt.xlabel('Number of UFO Sightings')
plt.show()

We can also plot the number of sights by the number of movies released to see the corrolation between the two variables. It seems quite high.

Score:  0.685123549954

R-squared values show how well the prediction or the line fits the data. High r-squared values, like the one we got, suggest high correlation.

However, p-value for the intercept is .07 which is not less than .05 and this suggests that there is not a significant correlation between the number of Syfy and Fantasy movies released and the number of UFO sightings.

Even though the UFO skeptics would have liked to have seen a strong correlation; unfortunately, I could not reject the null hypothesis and could not show a significant between the movies and the number of UFO sightings.

Conclusion and Insight¶

Given that I could not reject my null hypothesis, it seems that there is not a significant correlation between the UFO sightings and the number of Syfy and Fantasy movies released.

However, even though, I could not find a reasonable correlation with the UFO sightings; hopefully, these tools have helped you get more insight into the sightings data and could be used again to find a different reliable correlation as more data is reported.
